6. Important interview trick
❗ This is very commonly asked:

“Can TreeMap contain duplicate keys?”

✔ Answer:

No. But duplicates are determined using Comparator logic, not equals()

`TreeSet` cannot store duplicate elements because of how its internal data structure works.

Internally:

```java
TreeSet  --->  TreeMap
```

And `TreeMap` stores data using:

```text
Red-Black Tree
```

A Red-Black Tree is a type of Binary Search Tree (BST).

---

# Core Technical Reason

A `TreeSet` determines duplicates using:

```java
compareTo()
```

OR

```java
Comparator.compare()
```

NOT using `==`

NOT primarily using `hashCode()`

---

# Internal Logic

When inserting a new element:

TreeSet compares the new value with existing nodes.

If comparison result becomes:

```java
0
```

then TreeSet says:

```text
"Element already exists"
```

and insertion is rejected.

---

# Internal Flow

Suppose:

```java
TreeSet<Integer> set = new TreeSet<>();

set.add(50);
set.add(30);
set.add(70);
set.add(30);
```

---

# Step-by-Step Internally

## Insert 50

Tree empty.

```text
50
```

---

## Insert 30

Comparison:

```java
30.compareTo(50) = -1
```

Go LEFT.

```text
   50
  /
30
```

---

## Insert 70

Comparison:

```java
70.compareTo(50) = +1
```

Go RIGHT.

```text
   50
  /  \
30   70
```

---

## Insert Duplicate 30

Start from root:

### Compare:

```java
30.compareTo(50) = -1
```

Go left.

Now compare with existing 30:

```java
30.compareTo(30) = 0
```

Now TreeSet concludes:

```text
Duplicate found
```

Insertion stops.

---

# EXACT INTERNAL CONDITION

Inside `TreeMap.put()` logic:

```java
if (cmp < 0)
    goLeft();

else if (cmp > 0)
    goRight();

else
    return oldValue; // duplicate key
```

That:

```java
cmp == 0
```

is the technical reason duplicates are rejected.

---

# VERY IMPORTANT

## TreeSet Uses "Ordering" To Detect Duplicates

Not equality alone.

This is HUGE.

---

# Example With Custom Objects

```java
class Employee implements Comparable<Employee> {

    int id;

    Employee(int id) {
        this.id = id;
    }

    public int compareTo(Employee e) {
        return this.id - e.id;
    }
}
```

---

## Insert

```java
TreeSet<Employee> set = new TreeSet<>();

set.add(new Employee(101));
set.add(new Employee(101));
```

---

# Internally

```java
101 - 101 = 0
```

So TreeSet thinks:

```text
Same element
```

Second object rejected.

Even though:

```java
new Employee(101) != new Employee(101)
```

Different memory addresses.

---

# CRITICAL INTERVIEW POINT

## TreeSet duplicate detection depends on:

| Method               | Used?                  |
| -------------------- | ---------------------- |
| compareTo()          | YES                    |
| Comparator.compare() | YES                    |
| equals()             | NO (mostly irrelevant) |
| hashCode()           | NO                     |

---

# Dangerous Situation

If compareTo is wrong:

```java
public int compareTo(Employee e) {
    return 1;
}
```

Now TreeSet thinks EVERY element is different.

Duplicates get inserted incorrectly.

---

# Another Dangerous Example

```java
public int compareTo(Employee e) {
    return 0;
}
```

Now TreeSet thinks ALL elements are same.

Only one element stored.

---

# Why compareTo() Is Used?

Because TreeSet must maintain:

```text
SORTED ORDER
```

To place elements correctly in BST,
it must compare values.

So duplicate detection naturally comes from comparison.

---

# Internal TreeMap Structure

Actually TreeSet stores:

```java
TreeMap<E, Object>
```

Like this internally:

```text
Key      Value
30   -> PRESENT
50   -> PRESENT
70   -> PRESENT
```

`PRESENT` is just a dummy object.

Since keys in TreeMap cannot duplicate,
TreeSet also cannot duplicate.

---

# Technical Summary

| Feature          | Reason                |
| ---------------- | --------------------- |
| No duplicates    | compareTo() returns 0 |
| Internal DS      | Red-Black Tree        |
| Backed by        | TreeMap               |
| Duplicate check  | Ordering comparison   |
| equals() used?   | No                    |
| hashCode() used? | No                    |

---

# One-Line Technical Definition

```text
TreeSet rejects duplicates because
its underlying Red-Black Tree cannot contain two nodes
whose comparison result is 0.
```
